    <div class="modal custom fade" id="languageUse" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="languageUse" aria-hidden="true">
      <div class="modal-dialog modal-lg" role="document">
        <div class="modal-content">
          <div class="modal-header text-center">
            <h5 class="modal-title" id="languageUse">
              Language Without Information Exchange
            </h5>
          </div>
          <div class="modal-body">
            This paper is an attempt to revive a once-lively program in the philosophy of language—that of reducing linguistic phenomena to facts about mental states and actions of language users. Though recent years have seen a growing attitude of skepticism toward this project, I argue that various problems which generated it find their source not in the project itself, but rather in specific implementations of it. Previous theorists tended to assume that language functions essentially as mechanism for cooperative information exchange, which naturally led to metasemantic accounts grounding language use in illocutionary action (conveying a content with some kind of force). I argue that when this assumption is relaxed, a metasemantics grounding language in locutionary action (merely conveying a content) emerges as a more viable proposal, displaying the flexibility to accommodate issues which were taken to be intractable for previous theories—such as the metasemantics of subsentential constituents and non-standard speech.
          </div>
          <div class="modal-footer">
            <button type="button" class="btn btn-secondary" data-dismiss="modal">Close</button>
