    <div class="modal custom fade" id="onMeaning" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="onMeaning" aria-hidden="true">
      <div class="modal-dialog modal-lg" role="document">
        <div class="modal-content">
          <div class="modal-header text-center">
            <h5 class="modal-title" id="onMeaning">
              On Meaning Without Use
            </h5>
          </div>
          <div class="modal-body">
            In this paper I defend an elegant but largely abandoned metasemantic picture according to which linguistic communication is grounded in conventions of use, ushered into broad philosophical discourse by David Lewis in his seminal (1969) Convention. I will defend this picture against a famous criticism—put forward by John Hawthorne, developing an objection by Stephen Schiffer—known as the problem of meaning without use. This criticism is commonly taken to be decisive, prompting various retreats and surrenders by the most prominent proponents of this picture, and contributing to the project’s eventual decline. I argue that the issue of meaning without use is in fact innocuous—and that if the broadly Lewisiean metasemantic picture is to be abandoned, it should not be on this basis. While this goal is focused, it is not narrow or unambitious; Lewis's theory of convention provided a powerful tool for theorists interested in reducing linguistic communication to facts about actions and mental states, the core ideas of which can be seen in most serious attempts to systematically implement this project.If I manage to dispel a major worry for this framework, it will be no small victory towards vindicating the broader reductive project.
          </div>
